7 9–101.1.
8 (a) In this section, “abuse” has the meaning stated in § 4–501 of this article.
9 (b) In a custody or visitation proceeding, the court shall consider, when deciding
10 custody or visitation issues, evidence of abuse by a party against:
11 (1) the other parent of the party’s child;
12 (2) the party’s spouse; or
13 (3) any child residing within the party’s household, including a child other
14 than the child who is the subject of the custody or visitation proceeding.
15 (c) If the court finds that a party has committed abuse against the other parent
16 of the party’s child, the party’s spouse, or any child residing within the party’s household,
17 the court shall make arrangements for custody or visitation that best protect:
18 (1) the child who is the subject of the proceeding; and
19 (2) the victim of the abuse.
20 9–101.2.
21 (a) Except as provided in subsection (b) of this section, unless good cause for the
22 award of custody or visitation is shown by clear and convincing evidence, a court may not
23 award custody of a child or visitation with a child:
24 (1) to a parent who has been found by a court of this State to be guilty of
25 first degree or second degree murder of the other parent of the child, another child of the
26 parent, or any family member residing in the household of either parent of the child; or
27 (2) to a parent who has been found by a court of any state or of the United
28 States to be guilty of a crime that, if committed in this State, would be first degree murder
29 or second degree murder of the other parent of the child, another child of the parent, or any
30 family member residing in the household of either parent of the child.
31 (b) If it is in the best interest of the child, the court may approve a supervised
32 visitation arrangement that assures the safety and the physiological, psychological, and

